## Implementation

The `Customer` interface also needs two new fields the existing type doesn't have. I'll define those explicitly.

```typescript
// types.ts (modified)
export interface Customer {
  id: string;
  tier: "premium" | "gold" | "standard";  // kept for backward compat, but no longer drives discount
  accountCreatedAt: Date;                   // NEW — required for AC1/AC2/AC3
  lastPurchasedAt: Date | null;             // NEW — required for AC2/AC3 (null = never purchased)
}
```

```typescript
// calculateDiscount.ts (modified)

const DAYS_30_MS  = 30 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000;
const DAYS_90_MS  = 90 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000;

export function calculateDiscount(customer: Customer, now: Date = new Date()): number {
  const accountAgeMs = now.getTime() - customer.accountCreatedAt.getTime();

  // AC1: New customer — account age < 30 days
  if (accountAgeMs < DAYS_30_MS) {
    return 0.05;
  }

  // AC2 / AC3: Returning customer — account age >= 30 days
  const hasRecentPurchase =
    customer.lastPurchasedAt !== null &&
    now.getTime() - customer.lastPurchasedAt.getTime() < DAYS_90_MS;

  if (!hasRecentPurchase) {
    return 0.03; // AC2: win-back rate
  }

  return 0;     // AC3: active customer, no discount
}
```

**Key decision:** `now` is injected as a parameter (default `new Date()`). This makes all three ACs trivially testable without mocking system time.

